.TH "keep\-running" "1" "April 22, 2026" "Version 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
\f[B]keep\-running\f[R] \- a wrapper utility that launches a command and
relaunches it when it terminates
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]keep\-running\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \&...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]] \&...
.PP
\f[B]run\-constantly\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \&...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]] \&...
.PP
\f[B]run\-until\-failure\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \&...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]] \&...
.PP
\f[B]run\-until\-success\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \&...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]] \&...
.SH DESCRIPTION
The base form of utility simply keeps a program running, relaunching it
whenever it exits.
.PP
\f[B]run\-constantly\f[R] is an alias for \f[B]keep\-running\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]run\-until\-failure\f[R] is equivalent to / an alias for
\f[B]keep\-running \-u f\f[R].
It respawns user command until it returns a non\-zero exit code.
.PP
\f[B]run\-until\-success\f[R] is equivalent to / an alias for
\f[B]keep\-running \-u s\f[R].
It responds user command until it returns with the exit code of zero.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-u [s|f]\f[R]
This parameter defines respawn loop exit condition.
\f[B]`s'\f[R] orders to stop relaunching when the command exit code is
zero (same as running \f[B]run\-until\-success\f[R]), while
\f[B]`f'\f[R] exit the loop when user command fails (same as running
\f[B]run\-until\-failure\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\-r NUMBER\f[R]
limits the number of times the supplied command can be launched.
By default it keeps respawning the command indefinitely.
.TP
\f[B]\-R BURST:RATE\f[R]
This parameter controls the relaunch frequency.
It assumes that, under normal conditions, the command will not terminate
often.
BURST \- The number of times the command can relaunch immediately before
throttling begins.
RATE \- The minimum required interval (in ms) between relaunches once
the burst is exhausted.
If BURST is 0 or 1, throttling engages immediately, ensuring the command
does not restart more than once per RATE interval.
.TP
\f[B]\f[R]
In other words, if a command exits immediately, it is allowed to
relaunch without delay for a total of BURST attempts.
Once this limit is reached, the utility enforces a mandatory RATE (in
milliseconds) sleep between subsequent restarts to throttle the
execution speed.
.TP
\f[B]\-E EXIT_CODE\f[R]
custom error exit code; enables the user to differentiate between the
command failure and the utility exit error (see EXIT STATUS section for
details)
.TP
\f[B]\-D PATH\f[R]
debug/log file path.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\f[B]keep\-running \-R 10:2000 \-r 2000 my\-favorite\-watchdog arg1\f[R]
keeps relaunching the user process allowing up to 2000 respawns; applies
rate limiting for frequent command restarts allowing 10 relaunches in
one single initial burst (when a process exists very
frequently/instantly and gets relaunched immediately) and then limiting
the frequency of respawns to minimum 2000 milliseconds between launches,
pausing/sleeping in between.
.SH EXIT STATUS
\f[B]keep\-running\f[R] and variants exit with the following status:
.IP
.EX
0       upon success
123     when this utility encounters a problem; customizable with \-E
.EE
.PP
Exit code 123 is returned when the utility itself encounters an abnormal
situation, e.g.\ when a parameter is invalid of respawn count is
exceeded.
This code is customizable with \-E option.
.PP
Exit code from \f[B]run\-until\-failure\f[R] is never zero.
It is either 123 (customizable) or it is the exit code returned by the
user command.
